Predicting House Prices in Philadelphia with OLS

Timothy Oliver and Jarred Randall

11 October 2023

Introduction

The housing market is very volatile, so understanding what factors contribute to that volatility is extremely important. Zillow has expressed concerns that their housing market predictions are not as accurate as they could be. The biggest contributor to the inaccurate predictions of their current model is that they do not factor in enough local intelligence. Local intelligence is defined as a homes spatial relationships with its surrounding environment such as distances to amenities and public services or the amount of crime that occurs in a specified vicinity of the house. Our strategy is to create a linear model that considers a current Zillow database about given homes in Philadelphia and incorporate open data for nearby amenities such as landmarks, parks, school catchments, and neighborhoods to synthesize a more accurate housing market predictive model. Although some of the chosen spatial relationships showed a strong relationship with housing prices such as school catchments and distance from a farmers market the model is unable to predict home sales prices with a high degree of certainty. The following report will further explain our process, methods, results, and findings.

Data Gathering and Processing

Building an accurate model that can help predict housing prices requires a lot of information. Our answer to obtaining such information comes in the form of open-source data. For this predictive model we gather data from the city of Philadelphias open data platform and American Community Survey 5-year estimates for 2020. After all the necessary data is collected, the exploratory data analysis process begins where it is ensured that additional information is a good fit for the predictive model.

In addition to previously verified home prices and internal characteristics from our existing Zillow database, Philadelphia-specific information was retrieved from Open Data Philly. Some notable additions include amenities like university and college locations, parks, and farmer market sites. The American Community Surveys 2020 data for Philadelphia Census tracts introduce some demographic information, and areal divisions of the county such as school catchments, neighborhoods, and planning districts are also gathered for our presented model.

In many cases, the spatial data from Open Data Philly was used to identify selections of homes within a set distance from amenities and the type of such an amenity if such information was included. For instance, parks were categorized by a site class field in their data with an implicit ranking from A -> B -> C -> D and a special category of S. The highest class of park within a half-mile from a home was recorded with the distance also stored where applicable. The areal division data was used to potentially identify common spatial considerations across home observations.

Testing Variables

After analyzing all the collected data, we extracted variables from each data set to test and see their relationship with home sales price. The variables we chose are subdivided into two different categories: Internal home characteristics and spatial relationships. Internal home characteristics variables are physical features of a house that could affect its sales price. These variables include:

  • The total number of bedrooms

  • the total number of bathrooms

  • the houses number of fireplaces

  • the houses total area (or sqare footage)

  • the total livable area of the house

  • the year the house was built

The spatial relationship variables

look at all the amenities and structures that are within a certain distance of the house. These spatial variables include:

  • 1/2-mile proximity to a university or college campus

  • 1/8-mile proximity to a park or recreational facility and the class of said park

    • alongside distance to the closest class A park (large park with many amenities)

  • 1/8-mile proximity to a landmark and its type (historic site, public attraction, entertainment venue)

  • Which school catchment the house is in

  • If the house is in a census tract with a median household income over $120,000

  • The average distance to the five closest houses that sold for a million dollars or more.

Summary Statistics of the Internal Home Characteristics

After gathering and sythesizing our data into our stated selection of variables, a summary statistics chart was built to summarize each continuous or numerical one. This chart helps to communicate a large amount of information simply by providing each variables standard deviation, mean, median, maximum, and minimum values. The standard deviation describes the usual absolute difference between the mean (or average) and each observation.

This correlation matrix helps provide a way to visualize how different numerical variables are related (correlated) to each other in our model. Spatial variables in our model that denote numerical distance like near_hist_site (near a historical site) and near_park_a (near a large park with many amenities) show low correlations. The k-nearest neighbor variables (highsale_nn1-5) which detail the average distance to the k (specified amount of) nearest houses that sold for over $1 million all show a high positive correlation. These highly correlated variables can be used as proxies for each other and only one is necessary for the purposes of this model.

Other notable correlations include: The amount of frontage (the space between road and the building) and the total area have a strong positive correlation, A positive correlation between the houses exterior and interior conditions, as well as correlations between miscellaneous and redundant variables like geographic ward, parcel number, object id and musaid. While the redundant, database-specific variables would not be considered for the model, this correlation matrix has helped identify how some of our existing and added variables should be minimized to reduce collinearity. Collinearity is when independent variables are correlated and often recognized when two variables have correlation coefficients higher than 0.8 or lower than -0.8. This means that information from the predictor variable is already captured by another used in the model.

This map explores the relationship between home sales price and the school catchment that the home is located in. School catchments are essentially geographical boundaries that determine which public school a child can attend based on their home address. This can affect home prices because catchments with better schools will create a greater living demand which could drive up home process. Based on visual examination of the map we can see that there is clustering of home price sales in the individual catchments. This means that the catchment for which the home is in can have an affect on home sale price.

  geom_sf(data = farmers_buffer, color = "red", fill = "transparent",linewidth=1,show.legend = TRUE, size = 2) + 
  labs(title="Philadelphia Home Sale Prices Within 1/4 Mile of a Farmers Market") +
  mapTheme() +
  theme(
    legend.title = element_text(margin = margin(b = 10)) # Adjust the bottom margin
  )

This map explores if there is a relationship between access to farmer markets and home sales price in Philadelphia. In this map access is defined as a walkable distance of 1/8 mile to or from a farmers market. Farmers markets tend to be made up of local farmers and artisanal purveyors, both of which normally charge more for items than a supermarket would. This suggests that people would need to be making a higher income to afford to shop at farmers markets. In this map were looking to see if the locations of farmers markets are more generally found in areas with higher home prices.

Methods

Following the collection and exploration of pre-existing and additional data, we are ready to begin the formation of our linear model and gauging its effectiveness.

This process begins with splitting our set of 23,781 houses into a training set used to build our linear fit model and a testing set which will be predicted upon. We choose to make our training set 80% of our data due for two main reasons. First, our decision to include housing records with extremely large or low sales prices such as those with sales prices of $0 and $5,990,000 would have strong effects on a linear model, but some details about Philadelphia at the time of purchase could be captured in those prices. Having more training data will ideally lower the adverse effects on the prediction model while still giving a portion of the relationships that are difficult for people to see. Secondly, the 80% training to 20% testing split is an often accepting starting point for model evaluation especially given our data size of 23,781 houses.

After splitting our data, the lm function is used to create our linear model with respect to our previously discussed variablesboth internal home characteristics and spatial ones. The accuracy is them measured by

  1. Predicting the sales price of homes in the testing set

  2. Finding the absolute error between predicted and observed sales prices as dollar values and percents

  3. Performing a k-fold cross validation that performs steps 1 & 2 again with smaller, different validation sets 100 times and returns accuracy metrics

  4. Showing the mean errors of the model predictions visually with maps and scatter plots

  5. Testing generalizability of the model with respect to racial and income contexts.

Results

With the completion of our methods, we can observe our models accuracy and proposed correlation of variables with sale price as seen with the following tables below. The first showcases the linear model summary created from the training set. Many variables are categorical; therefore, there is a comparison element for sales prices with the default being the main focus of discussion here. The second simply displays the mean absolute percent error (MAPE) and mean absolute error (MAE) between the predicted sales price and observed sales price for all houses in the testing set. The first value is a percentage while the second is in dollars.

The regression coefficient, shown in the chart beside variable names, provides the expected change in the dependent variable (sales price) for a one unit increase in the independent variable (chosen test variables) when the variable is not categorical. The regression coefficient also tells us if the chosen test variables have either a positive or negative relationship with home sales prices in Philadelphia. For example, homes within the geographical bounds of the General Phillip Kearny school catchment see an increase of about $48,960 in home sales price so $48,960 + the intercept price of $370,369 would equal a average home sales price of $419,329 for homes located in that school catchment. However, homes located in the Alexander Comly school catchment area have a negative relationship with home sales prices with a decrease of $91,853. This means that the average sales price for homes in this school catchment is $278,516 ($370,369 - $91,853). From this we can see that school catchment location have a strong correlation (relationship) with home sales prices in Philadelphia.

Given the many categories for variables in this data set, the base case for this linear model is a house within an eighth of a mile from a park of site class A located in the Chestnut Hill neighborhood and the Adaire & Alexander school catchment. Additionally, any numerical values associated with the house like number of rooms or total area in square feet would be zero. With these details in mind, the intercept of this model states that such a house can be expected to be priced at $36,821.10.

Presence near a site class A park does not seem remarkable for a house with similar homes near a class B or C park being expected to cost $13,000 or $5,000 more, respectively. On the whole, the existence of a park nearby does appear to appreciate sales price somewhat, but the relationship between the class of the park site and price remains uncertain.

The price of a home does appear to have a large correlation with neighborhood with prices of similar homes in other neighborhoods compared to those in Chestnut Hill depreciating by up to $250,000. This model communicates Chestnut Hill as the second most expensive neighborhood for homes just behind Washington Square. Likewise, homes in neighborhoods outside the 10 most expensive neighborhoods found in our data are quite similar in price to the Manayunk neighborhood when averaged together in our model.

Similarly, the school catchments of have a wide range in prices despite the larger number of categories161 total catchments. The default case of the Adaire & Alexander school catchment is quite expensive with similar homes in many other catchments selling for $100,000 to $300,000 less. Only a handful of school catchments like the Fann Jackson Coppin catchment have a higher price at $50,000 more. The other variables that were binary or numerical were slightly more straightforward. Proximity to other amenities like a farmers market or university raised prices by about $10,000. The addition of a bedroom to a home raises is price by about $8,600 whereas a fireplace would by $53,645. Lastly, a single square foot of more livable area in the home was interpreted to raise the price by $204.69. The models R-squared or expected percentage of variance that the collected variables explain is 0.684.

In regards to predictions on the testing set, there is a mean difference of $140,567.69 dollars between the predicted sales price and the observed price corresponding to an average difference of 56%. A variety of factors could contribute to this and encourage additional modifications to the models design.

To test the accuracy of our model the datasets are randomly split into training data and testing data. The training data is used to train a model to make sales predictions and the testing data is used to test the accuracy of the model. After running the regression analysis testing the accuracy of the model, we are given the results in the forms of intercepts, coefficients, R-Squared, and Adjusted R-Squared.

The number paired with variables that is within the parenthesis is called the Standard Error. The standard error is estimate of the standard deviation of the coefficient. In the case of homes located within the Alexander Comly school catchment area the standard error is $19,535 which means that there is a $19,535 difference between the mean (average) sales price of each observation. The R-squared value tells us how well the regression model fits the observed data values, meaning, the percentage of how accurate our predictive model is at predicting housing prices with our 23,930 house modelling dataset. The R-Squared for this model is roughly .69 or 69% accurate in predicting housing prices under our given dataset. The MAE or Mean Absolute Error is the absolute difference between the actual value and the predicted value. In this model the MAE is $154,669. The MAPE or Mean Absolute Percentage Error is the mean absolute percentage between the actual and predicted value. In this model the MAPE is $0.56%. This means that the model is not accurate in predicting sales prices because it is more wrong than right.

This histogram showcases a Morans I evaluation of the spatial lag in prediction errors with the orange vertical line amidst its 999 permutations denoted with gray bars. While 999 simulations are conducted to observe if the errors are spatially correlated, the observed Morans I value, the position or ranking of the observed can change based on the set of simulations. Across the sets we have observed, the observed might be fairly high or average in ranking. Though the values remain low at 0.1 or less. We interpret this as lag in prices being relatively random.

Discussion

Overall, the model created a linear model considering data already present in the current Zillow database about given homes and open data about nearby amenities like landmarks and parks or the areal units describing around the home like school catchments or neighborhoods.

While not extremely accurate with a mean absolute percent error (MAPE) of 56, our model can be expected to predict within $140,567.69 above or below the actual observed sales price. The importance of each variable in the prediction varies with 68.63% of the variation in prices being predicted throughout. The largest significance in variable correlation goes to the total livable area and number of key rooms in the home, the school catchment and neighborhood it is located in, and specific spatial considerations like the existence of a farmers market within 1/8 of a mile from the home. While these spatial variables have stronger correlations to sales price than others or higher recorded significance in our model, the direct cause of this relationship remains unknown. For instance, proximity of a home to a farmers market might be a simple sign of other desirable amenities also being closely located to the home as well. The model appears to predict best when the actual sales price of a house is between $750,000 and $1,500,000. The vast range and scarcity of samples outside this interval led to consistend overestimation of extremely low and high observed house prices and underestimation of those priced just before $750,000. Likewise, maps of our test set predictions speaks to the created models ability to catch general areas for specific variations in price like Manayuk and Far Northeast Philadelphia. However, Central City has some variation that is not immediately explainable to the human observer.

In regards to different contexts, the model performed quite similarly to the baseline regression with changes close to or smaller than 1%. The contexts of high and low income were different in location to the second context of majority white vs.majority non-white areas but had otherwise similar divisions in mean prices across the areas. The similar error metrics across demographic contexts and slight improvement in absolute error in our 100-fold cross validation ($140,567.69 compared to $109,303.90 in the cross validation) point towards a generalizable model that can perform with similar effectiveness across different demographic groups. Potential improvements to model design like minimizing collinearity in independent variables or finding additional significant data to include would likely improve the models accuracy to have a lower MAPE while retaining the generalizability it has showcased. The model presented here is a solid starting point for an effective, yet generalizable predictive model for home prices using local intelligence.
